default5. 
defaultWe have been struck by the way those who are 'for' academy status are unprepared to engage in debate with those of us who oppose. In our experience, those 'pushing' for aca
defaultdemy status are often the head and chair of governors of a school. Typically, they will arrange for the governing body to be addressed by another proponent of academies who gives all the arguments 'for' whilst no-one is invited to put the case 'against'
default 
default(
defaultw
defaulthere we have been invited we have been 
defaultwell-received.) 
defaultSometimes the academy proponent is portrayed as a ‘neutral’ who is giving 
default‘the facts’ in an unbiased way. 
default'Consultation' with parents usually follows the same pattern and staff are 
defaultoften
default simply informed. The impression is given that the change is going to happen, 
defaultit is non-controversial and 
defaultthat 
defaulteveryone agrees it's self evidently a 'good thing'. 
defaultWe are aware of many instances where staff feel afraid to express opinions that might oppose 
defaulta potential academisation
default.
