default15. 
defaultIn conclusion, 
defaultwe very much welcome the Select Committee review, and the opportunity to present our arguments.  As we indicate, we are a relatively small group, and we are all volunteers.  We have no resources of an appreciable nature.  We are clear that we are opposed t
defaulto 
defaulta
defaultcademies and 
defaultf
defaultree 
defaults
defaultchools, for the reasons indicated.  However, our concerns are not just that our criticisms of 
defaulta
defaultcademies and 
defaultf
defaultree 
defaults
defaultchools 
defaultappear
default 
defaultto be 
defaultwell
default-
defaultfounded, 
defaultbut that genuine community debate on these issues is often being stifled.  As a group 
defaultof local people, we are well connected to parents, governors and those who work in schools.  We therefore hear what is happening in schools, and how decisions are being made. We know what is going on.  However, as a small group of local campaigners, with v
defaultery few resources, we are left with anecdot
defaultal
default rather than systematic evidence.  
defaultWe also understand that those who seek to stifle debate in the ways we have described have no interest in opening themselves up to serious research
default into
default their processes of gove
defaultrnance.
default&#xa0;
default16. 
defaultOur view is 
defaultthat 
defaultthere is an urgent need to commission serious, detailed and independent research into many of the issues identified in this submission.  There is much that is rotten in the governance of schools currently if our stories are re
defaultplicated on a much wider scale
default across the country
default.  Much more difficult and penetrating questions need to be posed, and 
defaultappropriate
default 
defaultresearch undertaken, if we are to develop a
default 
defaultmore authentic understanding of what is really happening in our schools.  We 
defaulthope that the Select Committee Review is the start of this process, and that much more work will be undertaken as a result.
